    <title>Stochastic Integral

Here’s the confusing aspect, if X is a random number dX means X(t=2) - X(t=1). So for two different instances I have two different random numbers. When I say integrate dX^2 I am actually saying
(X(t(p)) - X(t(p-1)))^2 where p is from 1 to n and n can be infinite. How do we expect this integral to converge? For example take 2 random numbers in excel, compute their difference. Take a million cases and finally add them, which is equivalent to the stochastic integral. Does it converge? No! 

We never say that the integral converges in normal sense. It converges in _MEAN SQUARE SENSE_. Now many of us might have memorized this proof but again it’s easy to memorize but hard to apply or remember. 
￼


All in all the integral converges in the MEAN SQUARE sense and hence we write in short cut dX^2 = dt, and that’s why financial prices are not perfect like mathematical formulas or physics equations. It all depends on probability which is again risk neutral probability.  

PS: X(t2) - X(t1) is normally distributed, here I have used wiener process definition that increments are normally distributed and for a standard normal distribution mean is 1. 






